WEBVTT

00:00.066 --> 00:02.800
[CHUCKLING]
Okay, I'll see you guys soon. Yeah.

00:04.367 --> 00:05.734
Nice of you to join us.

00:06.200 --> 00:08.467
-Sorry.
-It's not that nice.

00:08.533 --> 00:10.600
Sam, come on,
your lunch is getting cold.

00:11.000 --> 00:13.066
We don't have time for lunch.
We can grab lunch on the way.

00:13.133 --> 00:14.433
On the way to what?

00:14.500 --> 00:17.166
-The Super Sports Expo!
-[CROWD CHEERS]

00:17.600 --> 00:19.233
Come on, you promised you'd go.

00:19.467 --> 00:20.467
Are you sure?

00:20.533 --> 00:22.667
'Cause that doesn't sound like
something I would do.

00:23.500 --> 00:24.500
Ha, ha.

00:24.567 --> 00:26.100
It's gonna be great. They-They got...

00:26.166 --> 00:28.266
They got football jerseys,
they got baseball cards,

00:28.333 --> 00:30.533
and last year, they even had
a pair of Shaq's old shoes.

00:30.967 --> 00:34.467
-[CHUCKLES] Sounds fun.
-[SIGHING] Lizzie.

00:35.600 --> 00:36.600
Run!

00:38.133 --> 00:39.133
What?

00:39.266 --> 00:41.333
I need you to watch Matt
this afternoon.

00:41.834 --> 00:43.300
Uh, Lanny is coming over.

00:43.367 --> 00:45.867
I need you to watch
Matt and Lanny this afternoon.

00:45.934 --> 00:48.133
Mom. Mom, don't you think
that Matt and Lanny

00:48.200 --> 00:49.967
are incredibly mature for their age?

00:50.033 --> 00:51.734
I mean, they can stay home alone.

00:51.800 --> 00:52.800
No.

00:54.133 --> 00:56.133
You knew that wasn't gonna work.

00:56.200 --> 00:58.200
But I have plans. That is so unfair.

00:58.266 --> 00:59.834
Well, your plans have changed.

00:59.900 --> 01:01.100
[SCOFFS]

01:01.166 --> 01:05.266
Why even bother making plans?
I obviously exist just to watch Matt.

01:05.567 --> 01:08.166
-Jo McGuire, let's go!
-[CROWD CHEERS]

01:10.800 --> 01:12.800
[THEME SONG PLAYING]

01:53.767 --> 01:54.934
I almost forgot.

01:55.000 --> 01:56.734
We're going
to the Super Sports Expo today.

01:56.800 --> 01:58.367
You remember
the Super Sports Expo, right?

01:58.433 --> 01:59.433
That's where I found you.

01:59.500 --> 02:01.133
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

02:01.667 --> 02:04.300
Uh, Mom, Dad is talking
to the football. Again.

02:04.734 --> 02:06.867
Lizzie, Lizzie, Lizzie.

02:06.934 --> 02:08.633
That isn't just a football.

02:08.734 --> 02:12.066
That's an authentic
1986 Super Bowl football

02:12.133 --> 02:13.667
signed by Walter Payton.

02:13.734 --> 02:16.133
It's my favorite thing
in the whole world.

02:17.266 --> 02:19.100
-[CHUCKLING]
-Except for you guys, of course.

02:20.900 --> 02:22.700
-Honey, the car is idling.
-[TIRES SCREECH]

02:24.400 --> 02:26.400
Okay, Lizzie is in charge.

02:26.467 --> 02:29.200
Stay in the house and we'll be back
in a couple of hours.

02:29.266 --> 02:30.834
There's money in the kitchen
for pizza.

02:31.200 --> 02:33.333
Blah, blah, blah,
watch Matt for the rest of my life.

02:33.400 --> 02:35.200
Be miserable, blah, blah, blah.

02:35.266 --> 02:36.266
Got it.

02:36.934 --> 02:39.433
-Lizzie.
-This is so unfair.

02:39.500 --> 02:42.033
[SIGHING] Sometimes, life isn't fair.

02:42.100 --> 02:45.266
SAM: [YELLING] Super Sports Expo!
Super Sports Expo! Super Sports Expo!

02:45.600 --> 02:47.133
Like right now.

02:47.800 --> 02:48.800
Come on.

02:50.400 --> 02:52.800
Okay, here are the real ground rules.

02:52.867 --> 02:54.834
Don't bug me,
and when my friends come over,

02:54.900 --> 02:55.900
don't bug me.

02:55.967 --> 02:58.033
And if you get your
little head stuck in the toilet,

02:58.100 --> 02:59.467
don't bug me. Got it?

03:00.934 --> 03:02.433
Don't worry, Lanny. I mean,

03:02.567 --> 03:05.700
what are the odds of you getting
your head stuck in the toilet?

03:06.533 --> 03:07.533
Again.

03:08.834 --> 03:09.900
[YELPS, GRUNTS]

03:09.967 --> 03:11.100
LIZZIE: Worm.

03:12.400 --> 03:13.934
We got her good that time.

03:14.800 --> 03:16.700
Seven forty-two!

03:16.767 --> 03:18.133
Hut, hut, hike!

03:19.433 --> 03:22.166
McGuire drops back.
He starts to scramble.

03:22.600 --> 03:24.734
He sees Lanny breaking
for the end zone.

03:24.800 --> 03:27.066
He throws while he's going down!

03:33.433 --> 03:34.900
Lanny, you were covered.

03:34.967 --> 03:36.133
I had to throw the ball away

03:36.200 --> 03:38.266
or else it would have
been intercepted.

03:40.233 --> 03:41.200
Oops.

03:54.433 --> 03:55.567
What are you guys doing?

03:55.633 --> 03:57.233
Uh, not bugging you.

03:57.300 --> 04:00.300
[LAUGHS SARCASTICALLY]
Listen, Tweedledumb and Tweedledumber,

04:00.467 --> 04:02.400
this, right here, it's not a toy.

04:02.467 --> 04:04.967
This is one of Dad's
most prized possessions, okay?

04:05.033 --> 04:07.967
And if something happens to it,
that would bug me. Got it?

04:08.300 --> 04:10.500
My parents aren't paid enough
to do this job.

04:10.834 --> 04:12.734
I'm gonna go put this in a safe place.

04:13.200 --> 04:14.367
[CHUCKLES]

04:16.767 --> 04:19.767
You're right, Lanny,
she does take after my mom.

04:20.600 --> 04:23.533
Matt and Lanny were messing around
with my dad's autographed football,

04:23.600 --> 04:25.900
so I had to put it
in the hall closet for safekeeping.

04:26.000 --> 04:29.367
You mean the authentic
1986 Super Bowl football,

04:29.467 --> 04:30.633
uh, signed by Walter Payton?

04:30.700 --> 04:32.066
No, Gordo, the other one.

04:32.767 --> 04:34.066
You have two?

04:34.467 --> 04:36.633
Uh, just put Miranda back
on the phone.

04:37.266 --> 04:39.700
-Lizzie wants to talk to you.
-Here, hold this.

04:40.333 --> 04:42.100
Hey, we're just gonna grab
a couple of books

04:42.166 --> 04:44.266
-and we'll be over soon, okay?
-Sounds good.

04:44.633 --> 04:46.600
-All right.
-[OBJECTS CLATTERING]

04:49.467 --> 04:52.333
We were getting a board game
off the top shelf of the closet

04:52.400 --> 04:54.066
and all this stuff came down.

04:54.133 --> 04:56.700
[SIGHS] At least the football is okay.
[BREATHES DEEPLY]

04:58.133 --> 05:00.567
Whoa! No, no, no, no, no, no, no!

05:02.200 --> 05:03.834
-[AIR HISSING]
-[LIZZIE GRUNTS]

05:05.367 --> 05:07.266
Go back! Do over! Rewind!

05:07.500 --> 05:09.667
[GASPS] This is not happening.

05:10.066 --> 05:11.066
Matt!

05:11.333 --> 05:13.066
Matt, you killed the football!

05:13.133 --> 05:14.500
I didn't kill the football.

05:14.567 --> 05:17.500
It was an accident. We didn't mean to.

05:17.567 --> 05:20.033
Matt, if you needed to get the game
and you couldn't reach it,

05:20.100 --> 05:21.967
why didn't you just call
for me to help you?

05:22.033 --> 05:25.300
-Because you told us not to bug you.
-[SIGHS]

05:25.600 --> 05:27.700
Great! Now he remembers.

05:28.000 --> 05:29.200
We are so busted.

05:29.266 --> 05:31.300
We're gonna be grounded forever
and it's your fault.

05:31.367 --> 05:34.867
Once again, Matt, you found a way
to ruin my life. Thanks a lot.

05:35.266 --> 05:38.300
You two just go upstairs, okay?
And stay there.

05:39.333 --> 05:42.166
[SIGHING IN EXASPERATION]

05:43.867 --> 05:46.266
LIZZIE: The bowling ball fell,
the football exploded,

05:46.333 --> 05:48.100
and my life is officially over.

05:49.467 --> 05:51.467
Where's a time machine
when you need one?

05:51.834 --> 05:52.834
Look on the bright side.

05:52.900 --> 05:55.266
At least your parents will never
force you to watch Matt again.

05:55.333 --> 05:57.233
Uh, not helping, Gordo.

05:57.533 --> 05:59.433
Well, maybe it's not
as bad as you think.

05:59.500 --> 06:00.734
Can you fix the ball?

06:00.800 --> 06:03.734
I don't know. Can I do that?
Can you fix a football?

06:04.200 --> 06:06.934
I don't know, but I'm sure
it can't get any worse.

06:07.000 --> 06:08.433
Hmm. Where's the football?

06:08.734 --> 06:09.734
Follow me.

06:11.400 --> 06:12.900
Okay, it has to be in here.

06:13.033 --> 06:15.467
Footballs don't just
get up and walk away.

06:15.533 --> 06:17.100
Not crushed ones anyway.

06:17.300 --> 06:19.033
[SCOFFS] Not helping, Gordo.

06:20.066 --> 06:22.133
Matt. [SHOUTS] Matt!

06:22.200 --> 06:24.567
You give me that football
right now, or else you're...

06:25.567 --> 06:27.667
Gone! [GRUNTS]

06:33.166 --> 06:35.266
"We went to fix the football.
We're really sorry."

06:35.333 --> 06:37.100
It's signed Matt and Lanny.

06:37.166 --> 06:39.367
Great, like I'm not
in enough trouble as it is.

06:39.667 --> 06:41.567
My little brother
and his friend are missing.

06:41.633 --> 06:45.166
We killed my dad's prized possession
and I have an English test tomorrow.

06:45.233 --> 06:47.533
Eek! Things couldn't be better. Whoa!

06:47.967 --> 06:50.300
Remember how I said
things couldn't get any worse?

06:51.600 --> 06:53.166
-I was wrong.
-[BOTH SCOFFING]

06:53.233 --> 06:55.033
BOTH: Not helping, Gordo.

06:57.066 --> 06:58.066
Come on.

06:59.667 --> 07:02.333
[SIGHS] That's it. I've called
all of their friends.

07:02.400 --> 07:05.000
Nobody has seen
or heard from Matt and Lanny.

07:05.834 --> 07:08.533
The only thing that's worse
than having Matt and Lanny around

07:08.600 --> 07:10.867
is not having Matt or Lanny around.

07:11.600 --> 07:13.066
I'm gonna be in so much trouble.

07:13.133 --> 07:15.000
Why don't we just go out
and look for 'em?

07:15.100 --> 07:17.367
Yeah, I mean,
how far can two 11-year-olds

07:17.433 --> 07:18.567
with a broken football go?

07:18.633 --> 07:20.734
Hello, my parents
are gonna be home soon, you guys.

07:20.800 --> 07:22.900
We don't have time
to find them and then get back.

07:23.333 --> 07:24.834
-[PHONE RINGING]
-Oh.

07:24.900 --> 07:26.633
-Matt?
-Lizzie?

07:26.700 --> 07:27.700
Mom?

07:28.700 --> 07:30.767
-Is everything okay?
-Um...

07:31.100 --> 07:33.500
It really depends
on your "definition" of "okay."

07:33.834 --> 07:36.300
Yeah, everything is, um...
Everything's fine.

07:36.600 --> 07:37.834
Is Matt behaving?

07:38.333 --> 07:40.567
Yeah. [STUTTERS]
Matt and Lanny are great.

07:40.633 --> 07:42.133
They're playing quietly upstairs.

07:43.400 --> 07:44.867
-Come here.
-What?

07:44.934 --> 07:47.333
She said Matt's behaving.
I think something's wrong.

07:48.367 --> 07:49.867
Well, here's the deal.

07:49.934 --> 07:52.233
Your dad and I are gonna be
a little late 'cause we got a flat.

07:52.667 --> 07:53.867
Oh, that's great!

07:53.934 --> 07:56.567
I mean, uh, that's greatly bad.

07:57.333 --> 07:59.700
So, we'll be home
in a couple of hours.

07:59.767 --> 08:02.166
Oh, okay, well, um,
you guys just take your time.

08:02.233 --> 08:03.700
You don't get out enough as it is.

08:03.767 --> 08:05.734
I've got everything
totally under control.

08:05.800 --> 08:07.867
-JO: <i>We'll see you guys soon.</i>
-Okay.

08:08.367 --> 08:10.333
Yes! Okay, we just bought some time.

08:10.400 --> 08:12.033
I know I would feel better

08:12.133 --> 08:13.800
if we had somebody
check in on those kids.

08:13.867 --> 08:15.667
Hey, I could have
my softball buddies swing by

08:15.734 --> 08:17.300
on their way home from practice.

08:17.967 --> 08:19.667
Well, it's better than nothing.

08:19.734 --> 08:20.734
Here's the plan, guys.

08:20.800 --> 08:23.033
Okay, you're gonna stay home
and man the phone.

08:23.100 --> 08:25.900
Oh, come on. I never get to do
any of the cool stuff.

08:25.967 --> 08:27.133
I wanna go with you guys.

08:27.200 --> 08:28.333
Gordo, Matt and Lanny like you.

08:28.400 --> 08:30.834
If they call, you can convince them
to come back home.

08:31.100 --> 08:33.767
-Fine, but can I order a pizza?
-[SCOFFS]

08:33.834 --> 08:36.367
Gordo, Matt and Lanny are missing.

08:36.433 --> 08:38.400
Uh, Lizzie is about
to be grounded for life

08:38.467 --> 08:40.700
and all you can think about is food.

08:41.300 --> 08:42.367
I'm hungry.

08:42.433 --> 08:44.533
Fine, Gordo, order a pizza
for yourself, okay?

08:44.600 --> 08:46.467
-Miranda, you're coming with me.
-Cool.

08:46.533 --> 08:48.400
-Everybody clear on the plan?
-Yeah.

08:48.767 --> 08:50.000
This plan better work.

08:50.133 --> 08:51.900
I think my parents might notice
that Matt is missing

08:51.967 --> 08:53.500
after a couple of days.

08:53.567 --> 08:55.066
Well, Mom will notice.

08:55.400 --> 08:56.767
Go, go, go.

09:40.633 --> 09:42.500
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

09:44.667 --> 09:46.834
[INDISTINCT ANIMAL SOUNDS]

10:06.300 --> 10:08.633
This is a Walter Payton
autographed football.

10:09.433 --> 10:11.266
You boys are in a lot of trouble.

10:11.667 --> 10:13.900
Sorry, son. I think he's passed.

10:13.967 --> 10:16.200
You mean, there's nothing we can do?

10:16.266 --> 10:18.266
Only a miracle can help you now.

10:18.800 --> 10:21.467
Of course, um,
you could just replace it.

10:21.533 --> 10:23.367
That's brilliant!

10:24.266 --> 10:26.166
You read my mind, Lanny.

10:26.367 --> 10:28.934
We're off to the Collectors Corner.

10:29.333 --> 10:30.333
Shalom.

10:32.100 --> 10:34.533
Once again, Gordo,
the responsible one,

10:34.600 --> 10:35.767
gets left behind.

10:36.233 --> 10:39.367
Lizzie and Miranda get to go out
and track down Matt and Lanny,

10:39.433 --> 10:41.333
while I'm here by myself.

10:42.367 --> 10:43.467
All alone.

10:44.200 --> 10:45.767
With cable.

10:46.633 --> 10:48.333
And video games.

10:49.367 --> 10:51.967
And a refrigerator full of food.

10:53.467 --> 10:56.467
For a smart guy,
I can be kind of dumb sometimes.

10:57.066 --> 10:59.500
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

11:25.700 --> 11:27.533
I think I will order a pizza.

11:28.734 --> 11:30.266
This is so typical of Matt.

11:30.333 --> 11:32.300
I mean, I set rules
and he breaks them.

11:32.433 --> 11:34.967
He doesn't think
of the consequences of his actions.

11:35.333 --> 11:36.734
[SCOFFS] Ruin Dad's football,

11:36.800 --> 11:39.600
ruin our lives.
Not exactly hard to remember.

11:39.900 --> 11:42.166
Sounding a little parental, aren't we?

11:42.233 --> 11:44.133
Miranda, you didn't lose
your little brother.

11:44.800 --> 11:46.734
What is this weird feeling I'm having?

11:46.967 --> 11:48.834
I'm worried?

11:49.533 --> 11:52.166
Lanny and Matt are out there
all alone, and it's my fault.

11:52.233 --> 11:53.734
It's not all your fault.

11:53.800 --> 11:55.834
I don't know what I'm gonna do
if we can't find them.

11:55.900 --> 11:56.900
We'll find them.

11:56.967 --> 11:58.533
Well, where do you think they'd go?

11:58.867 --> 12:01.567
Okay, I'm an 11-year-old geek
with a popped football

12:01.633 --> 12:03.367
signed by some famous guy.

12:03.667 --> 12:06.066
Oh, oh! Collectors Corner,
the comic book store.

12:06.133 --> 12:07.333
They sell footballs there?

12:07.400 --> 12:08.533
They sell everything there.

12:08.600 --> 12:10.934
It's like the geek version
of the mall. Come on.

12:11.834 --> 12:12.834
[DOORBELL RINGING]

12:12.900 --> 12:13.900
Mmm, pizza.

12:16.700 --> 12:19.200
Hey, so you guys
deliver pizza, too, huh?

12:19.266 --> 12:20.467
Mmm, pizza.

12:20.533 --> 12:22.000
Nah. Sam called us.

12:22.100 --> 12:23.967
We're just here
to check up on you guys.

12:24.200 --> 12:27.233
Oh. Well, uh, we're all doing great.

12:27.300 --> 12:30.867
Everything's A-Okay.
So, uh, see you later. [CHUCKLES]

12:36.367 --> 12:37.700
How dumb do you think we are?

12:38.100 --> 12:40.700
Uh, do you really want me
to answer that? [CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]

12:41.367 --> 12:45.633
We need, uh, visual confirmation
that everyone's A-Okay.

12:47.333 --> 12:48.834
Everyone's upstairs, uh...

12:49.200 --> 12:50.400
They'll be down in a second.

12:50.667 --> 12:53.533
Yeah, yeah. Go on.
Make yourselves at home.

13:09.133 --> 13:11.834
Come on. Walter Payton, Walter Payton.

13:12.934 --> 13:14.867
Walter Payton!

13:15.500 --> 13:17.333
[JUBILANT MUSIC PLAYS]

13:18.667 --> 13:19.900
Can I help you?

13:21.667 --> 13:22.667
What is this?

13:22.934 --> 13:25.567
It's an autographed
Walter Payton football.

13:25.633 --> 13:28.433
[SCOFFING] Oh, yeah, yeah,
perhaps in a former life.

13:28.834 --> 13:31.900
Now it's more like
an autographed Walter Payton pancake.

13:31.967 --> 13:32.967
[LAUGHS]

13:34.633 --> 13:35.767
[SIGHS]

13:36.433 --> 13:37.734
Me and Lanny, uh...

13:37.800 --> 13:38.967
This is Lanny.

13:39.100 --> 13:40.100
You see,

13:40.734 --> 13:43.667
it's kind of our fault
that this football is ruined.

13:43.734 --> 13:47.400
[SIGHS] It's my dad's and it's really,
really important to him.

13:47.734 --> 13:51.834
If I don't get him a new ball
then I'm in big trouble,

13:51.900 --> 13:54.867
and Lanny is in big trouble
and... [SNIFFLES]

13:54.934 --> 13:57.200
My sister,
who really didn't do anything,

13:57.266 --> 13:59.433
is gonna be in big trouble. [WHIMPERS]

13:59.500 --> 14:02.100
It sounds like
a really touching story here.

14:02.166 --> 14:03.433
[SOBS]

14:03.500 --> 14:07.333
So, we were hoping
maybe that you would exchange

14:07.433 --> 14:09.600
this ball for that nice new one.

14:09.667 --> 14:10.934
[SOBS]

14:12.567 --> 14:14.967
Hmm. Let me think about that.

14:17.266 --> 14:19.233
-No!
-[SOBBING LOUDLY]

14:20.734 --> 14:21.734
LIZZIE: Matt!

14:22.333 --> 14:23.667
[SIGHING] Matt.

14:30.100 --> 14:32.166
I thought you said
they'd be right down.

14:32.633 --> 14:34.066
Yeah, um...

14:34.266 --> 14:36.734
Hey! Say, you guys...
You guys like jokes?

14:36.800 --> 14:38.633
I got a great one. [GRUNTS]

14:39.633 --> 14:40.633
Okay, so,

14:41.033 --> 14:43.200
King of Norway, he, uh...
He goes out into the woods

14:43.266 --> 14:46.266
with his, uh... His, uh...
His number one hunter, right?

14:47.233 --> 14:49.266
-[LIZZIE SIGHS]
-MATT: How'd you guys find us?

14:49.667 --> 14:51.467
Well, we just pretended
we were a couple of geeks

14:51.533 --> 14:52.734
and where would we be?

14:54.233 --> 14:56.600
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY] Sorry.

14:57.000 --> 14:59.700
[SCOFFS] Matt, what were you thinking
taking off like that?

14:59.934 --> 15:01.734
And you better have a good answer.

15:02.066 --> 15:04.900
Well, we just thought,
what would you do in this situation?

15:05.266 --> 15:08.300
Well, you wouldn't get into trouble
in the first place,

15:08.767 --> 15:10.734
but you'd try to fix it.

15:11.667 --> 15:14.066
Aw, that's a pretty good answer.

15:14.133 --> 15:15.734
And that's what we tried to do.

15:16.266 --> 15:17.834
But you really scared me.

15:18.400 --> 15:19.934
-I did?
-Yeah, you did.

15:20.000 --> 15:22.066
And right now
the football doesn't even matter.

15:22.467 --> 15:24.266
All that matters is
that you two are okay,

15:24.333 --> 15:25.834
and we get you guys home safe.

15:27.266 --> 15:30.433
You know, I really hate to interrupt
this little Hallmark moment,

15:30.500 --> 15:32.266
but we do have
some parents to beat home.

15:32.333 --> 15:34.133
That's it. We're done for.

15:35.400 --> 15:36.400
It's not over.

15:36.467 --> 15:38.633
Nothing is over until I decide it is.

15:38.967 --> 15:40.400
Uh, no. Give me the football.

15:42.300 --> 15:44.467
-What are you doing?
-I'm saving the day.

15:44.934 --> 15:46.934
Excuse me. Uh, Mr. Comic Book Guy.

15:48.233 --> 15:49.533
You're wasting your time.

15:49.600 --> 15:51.900
I already told the little hobbit no.

15:52.266 --> 15:56.033
Uh, excuse me, sir. I have here
an autographed Walter Payton football.

15:56.100 --> 15:58.867
[CHUCKLES] Yeah, yeah,
in less-than-mint condition.

15:59.433 --> 16:02.233
[IMITATES CHUCKLE] I realize that,
but I was just wondering

16:02.300 --> 16:05.467
if maybe you would do a trade,
you know, give me another football.

16:06.300 --> 16:07.400
Interesting.

16:08.433 --> 16:09.533
Tell you what,

16:09.600 --> 16:12.734
I'll give you a Dick Butkus
for a deflated Walter Payton.

16:12.867 --> 16:13.867
[CLOCK TICKING]

16:16.900 --> 16:18.266
-[DING]
-Deal.

16:19.233 --> 16:21.367
[CHUCKLES] What's a Dick Butkus?

16:21.433 --> 16:23.967
I don't know, but he's all
we got right now. Come on.

16:27.433 --> 16:29.166
[CHUCKLING]

16:29.800 --> 16:32.133
-JEREMY: It's mine.
-So, the King of Norway says,

16:32.200 --> 16:35.633
"I thought he said he, uh...
I thought he said he was a moose."

16:35.700 --> 16:36.734
[MOUTHING]

16:36.834 --> 16:37.834
That was terrible.

16:39.467 --> 16:40.467
[MOUTHING]

16:40.734 --> 16:43.900
Um. Yeah, um, I guess it was.

16:43.967 --> 16:47.300
Uh, maybe that's 'cause I,
uh, told it wrong. Uh...

16:47.367 --> 16:48.967
Let me start again.
Well, how does it go?

16:49.033 --> 16:50.400
Uh, all right. Okay.

16:50.467 --> 16:53.533
So, uh, so the King of Norway,
he goes out into the woods

16:53.600 --> 16:55.433
with his number one hunter and...

16:55.500 --> 16:56.600
[THUDS]

16:57.266 --> 16:58.367
What's going on up there?

16:59.033 --> 17:00.033
Nothing. [CHUCKLES]

17:00.600 --> 17:01.900
[CLATTERING]

17:01.967 --> 17:03.266
Let's go check it out.

17:10.834 --> 17:12.533
What's going on up here?

17:12.600 --> 17:15.767
Oh, uh, um, n-nothing.

17:17.967 --> 17:19.133
Somebody is missing.

17:19.934 --> 17:21.433
-Where's Lizzie?
-Mm.

17:21.567 --> 17:23.400
-[DOOR CLOSES]
-Mom and Dad!

17:23.467 --> 17:25.700
SAM: Hello, anyone home?

17:26.900 --> 17:28.800
Come on, there's fire out there, yeah.

17:28.867 --> 17:29.867
They're over there.

17:32.066 --> 17:33.333
Help me, help me.

17:34.400 --> 17:35.367
[YELPS]

17:36.433 --> 17:37.533
-You okay?
-[PANTS]

17:41.467 --> 17:44.000
Hey, guys. Everything okay?

17:44.066 --> 17:45.333
-Fine.
-Great.

17:45.467 --> 17:46.467
Where's Lizzie?

17:49.133 --> 17:50.367
We can't find her.

17:50.433 --> 17:52.200
What do you mean you can't find her?

17:52.266 --> 17:53.266
SAM: Yeah.

17:56.000 --> 17:57.433
I'm sure you had
something to do with this.

17:57.500 --> 17:58.500
You're coming with me.

17:58.567 --> 17:59.734
[MIRANDA STUTTERS]

17:59.800 --> 18:00.800
Lanny!

18:01.767 --> 18:03.600
SAM: How could you
let her out of your sight?

18:06.533 --> 18:08.800
Hey, guys. Um...

18:08.967 --> 18:10.033
How was the sports thingy?

18:12.433 --> 18:13.533
[CHUCKLES]

18:24.133 --> 18:26.166
[VICTORY MUSIC PLAYING]

18:30.400 --> 18:33.467
And the high point of the day
was when I got my picture taken

18:33.600 --> 18:35.467
with last year's Super Bowl mascot.

18:35.700 --> 18:38.133
CROWD: Sam! Sam! Sam! Sam! Sam!

18:40.867 --> 18:43.533
So, did you kids do
anything fun today?

18:46.066 --> 18:47.066
Um.

18:47.367 --> 18:48.367
Let's see,

18:48.433 --> 18:51.033
destroying a football,
chasing Matt and Lanny across town,

18:51.100 --> 18:53.800
and sneaking back into the house
without getting caught.

18:54.166 --> 18:56.333
[CHUCKLING] Yeah. It was fun.

18:56.667 --> 18:58.233
Nah, we didn't have any fun.

18:58.467 --> 19:00.834
Yeah, just, uh, another boring day.

19:02.533 --> 19:04.333
Who would care to explain this to me?

19:05.000 --> 19:07.700
So close, yet still so busted.

19:08.233 --> 19:09.233
Explain what?

19:09.667 --> 19:12.300
How my Walter Payton signed football

19:12.367 --> 19:15.133
has magically become
a Dick Butkus signed football?

19:16.734 --> 19:18.033
It's all my fault.

19:18.266 --> 19:19.567
No, it's all my fault.

19:20.467 --> 19:21.467
BOTH: It's our fault.

19:21.533 --> 19:22.734
We ruined your football, Dad.

19:23.734 --> 19:25.066
Is this authentic?

19:25.133 --> 19:26.934
Well, the guy
at the store said it was.

19:27.500 --> 19:30.467
And you traded in
Dad's ruined football for this?

19:30.533 --> 19:32.066
We're really sorry.

19:33.633 --> 19:35.767
You guys are really good.

19:36.900 --> 19:38.600
Mom is taking this really well.

19:38.900 --> 19:40.400
SAM: What are you talking about?

19:40.467 --> 19:42.533
They ruined my beloved Payton
and brought back a Butkus!

19:42.600 --> 19:44.533
If I were you guys,
I would have just bought

19:44.600 --> 19:47.667
another football and signed it.
That's what I did.

19:48.500 --> 19:49.467
You did what?

19:49.667 --> 19:53.467
Uh, well, the football
that Lizzie and Matt ruined

19:53.533 --> 19:57.834
was actually a Walter Payton football
autographed by Jo McGuire.

19:58.900 --> 20:03.033
The real one fell into the fireplace
a couple of months ago, accidentally.

20:03.166 --> 20:04.700
-It did?
-Yeah.

20:04.900 --> 20:08.000
So, technically,
we didn't ruin Dad's football.

20:08.300 --> 20:12.967
And we got him a football signed
by someone more famous than Mom.

20:13.900 --> 20:16.166
So, technically,
we can't be grounded, right?

20:17.300 --> 20:18.300
Wrong.

20:18.834 --> 20:19.834
Not fair.

20:19.900 --> 20:21.433
That should be a penalty on Mom.

20:22.166 --> 20:23.700
Unnecessary grounding.

20:24.266 --> 20:27.100
Okay, from now on,
this football is off-limits

20:27.166 --> 20:28.667
to everyone in this house except me.

20:29.166 --> 20:30.300
JO: Honey?

20:31.867 --> 20:35.133
You know, I really am sorry
for messing up your day.

20:35.400 --> 20:36.600
I didn't mean to.

20:37.133 --> 20:39.900
Well, yes, I did,
but just not that much.

20:39.967 --> 20:43.367
[CHUCKLES] I know. And I'm sorry
for coming down on you so hard.

20:43.433 --> 20:44.433
I didn't mean to.

20:44.533 --> 20:47.166
Yeah, you did,
but, uh, you're my sister

20:47.233 --> 20:48.900
-and that's your job.
-I know.

20:49.333 --> 20:51.433
And I take my job very seriously.

20:53.333 --> 20:55.400
So, um, you do know
that if you ever need something,

20:55.467 --> 20:56.600
I'm here for you, right?

20:56.667 --> 20:58.033
-Yeah.
-Okay.

20:58.967 --> 21:01.233
Oh, but, um, if you ever
run away like that again,

21:01.300 --> 21:02.867
I'm gonna totally crush you.

21:03.300 --> 21:04.300
I know.

21:04.834 --> 21:05.934
[GASPS]

21:06.700 --> 21:09.233
Oh-ho, what you gonna do?
Come and get it.

21:13.100 --> 21:14.300
Mark.

21:15.567 --> 21:16.734
GORDO: What's my motivation?

21:16.800 --> 21:18.133
JEREMY: We'll beat you up.

21:18.200 --> 21:19.367
[LAUGHTER]

21:19.767 --> 21:21.066
-[MOUTHING]
-[RESOUNDING SLAP]

21:21.133 --> 21:22.500
Set, hike!

21:23.433 --> 21:25.166
Set 42!

21:25.233 --> 21:26.233
[BLOWS RASPBERRY]

21:26.300 --> 21:28.500
Oh, Lanny, I knew
you shouldn't have had those beans.

21:28.567 --> 21:31.166
Matt, you give me that football
right now, or else you're...

21:31.266 --> 21:32.300
[GRUNTS]

21:32.367 --> 21:33.367
WOMAN: Taboo.

21:33.433 --> 21:36.734
Taboo! Taboo! Taboo! Taboo!

21:39.433 --> 21:40.934
Let's see, destroying a football...

21:44.100 --> 21:46.867
Dick Butkus
for a deflated Walter Hill.

21:47.200 --> 21:48.567
Payton, uh, Walter Payton.

21:48.633 --> 21:50.900
Walter Hill
is an interesting director, though.

21:51.300 --> 21:52.300
Oh!

21:55.367 --> 21:56.667
-Uh, Gor...
-[RETCHING]

21:57.500 --> 21:59.233
-Matt.
-FEMALE CREW MEMBER: And that's a cut.

21:59.367 --> 22:01.300
-Is that good enough, Steve?
-STEVE: That's good.

22:01.900 --> 22:03.867
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
